Snyder is one of the most affluent and well-educated communities in Metropolitan Buffalo.<ref name=SAP7>"Snyder Action Plan", p. 7.</ref>  The residential population consists mostly of large single family homes on individual lots.<ref name=SAP7/>  The [[2000 United States Census]] average household income of $87,700 (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|87700|2000|r=0}}}} in current dollar terms) far exceeds the Buffalo regional average of $57,400 (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|57400|2000|r=0}}}}).<ref name=SAP18>"Snyder Action Plan", p. 18.</ref>  The Snyder population declined from 14,294 to 13,875 while the number of households increased from 5,469 to 5,574 between the [[1990 United States Census]] and the [[2000 United States Census]].<ref name=SAP18/>  During the decade the number of children age 5&ndash;17 and adults age 35&ndash;54 grew significantly while the young adults age 18&ndash;34 and adults over the age of 55 declined sharply.<ref name=SAP17>"Snyder Action Plan", p. 17.</ref>  The number of housing units grew from 5,662 to 5,739.<ref name=SAP18/> 1990 housing was 82.5% single-family housing.<ref name=SAP18/>  The busiest [[Automated teller machine|ATM]] in the entire Buffalo region is in Snyder.<ref name=SAP61>"Snyder Action Plan", p. 61.</ref>

The traditionally defined Snyder portion of Main Street had 180 businesses as of January 2002.<ref name=SAP63>"Snyder Action Plan", p. 63.</ref> The town has two theatres: Musical Fare Theater is a not for profit corporation on the Daemen College campus and Fisher-Towne Theater.<ref name=SAP64>"Snyder Action Plan", p. 64.</ref>

Starting in the 1950s [[zoning]] laws required that all new buildings be set back from the street and have private on-site parking.<ref name=SAP9>"Snyder Action Plan", p. 9.</ref>  The 21st Century zoning laws date back to 1976.<ref name=SAP13>"Snyder Action Plan", p. 13.</ref>

==Government==
There is no formal Snyder government.  The hamlet, like the rest of the town of Amherst, is served by the Town of Amherst Government and receives municipal services from the town.  It is serviced by entities such as the Amherst Police Department and the Town of Amherst Highway Department, although Main Street and Harlem Road are serviced by the [[New York State Department of Transportation]].<ref name=SAP52>"Snyder Action Plan", p. 52.</ref>  Residents of Amherst, including those in Snyder, pay taxes both to the Town of Amherst and the County of Erie.  However, the town tax is solely a school tax and the county collects the remaining town taxes for municipal services.

